import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---
<Base title="How to use" description="How to consume persona-atoms in your application.">
  <h1>How to use persona-atoms</h1>

  <h2>Read the catalog over HTTPS</h2>
  <p>Every artifact is served under stable URLs with correct content-types:</p>
  <pre><code>curl https://persona-atoms.com/exports/catalog.json
curl https://persona-atoms.com/atoms/voice-profile/warm-professional.json
curl https://persona-atoms.com/personas/reviewer-security/atom.json
curl https://persona-atoms.com/compositions/development-pod/atom.json
curl https://persona-atoms.com/schemas/composition-v1.json</code></pre>

  <h2>Resolve a persona composition</h2>
  <p>A persona composition lists references to atoms by URI and version. To instantiate the persona,
  fetch each referenced atom and assemble: voice profile → role definition → behavioural constraints → knowledge boundaries → tone parameters → optional work contract.</p>

  <pre><code>{`// pseudo-code
const composition = await fetch("/personas/reviewer-security/atom.json").then(r => r.json());
const voiceProfile = await fetch(uriToUrl(composition.voice_profile.ref)).then(r => r.json());
const roleDefinition = await fetch(uriToUrl(composition.role_definition.ref)).then(r => r.json());
const constraints = await Promise.all(
  (composition.behavioural_constraints ?? []).map(r => fetch(uriToUrl(r.ref)).then(r => r.json()))
);
const workContract = composition.work_contract
  ? await fetch(uriToUrl(composition.work_contract.ref)).then(r => r.json())
  : null;
const toneParams = await fetch(uriToUrl(composition.tone_parameters.ref)).then(r => r.json());
const systemPrompt = compilePersona({ voiceProfile, roleDefinition, constraints, toneParams, workContract });`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Resolve higher-order compositions</h2>
  <p>Panels, pods, and teams live under <code>/compositions/</code>. Their member references point to either personas or nested compositions.</p>

  <h2>Compatibility rules</h2>
  <p>Rules in <a href="/exports/catalog.json"><code>/exports/catalog.json</code></a> (under the <code>rules</code>
  key) declare predicates over atoms. Example: a <code>prompt-conformance</code> rule may require that a
  <code>voice-profile</code> and <code>tone-parameter</code> do not conflict on formality levels. A composition
  that violates a <code>require</code>-effect rule is malformed.</p>

  <h2>Runtime binding</h2>
  <p>persona-atoms ships the catalog and its JSON Schema. Runtime adapters that translate persona compositions
  into system prompts for specific runtimes (aish, Olympus, AutoGen) are available separately — they bind
  voice-profile atoms to tone directives and role-definition atoms to capability grants.</p>
</Base>
